Table 4
). The frequency modulation was absent and the harmonics were not clearly visible in the recording (
Fig. 8
).

The new species can be further easily distinguished from
L. botsfordi
( Lao Cai Province, northern Vietnam ), also with dark brownish red ventral surface with white speckling, by the following: ( 1 ) comparatively larger head size (HDL:SVL 0.41–0.47 versus 0.34–0.36 in
L. botsfordi
), ( 2 ) dense white speckling on the belly (versus only faint white spotting on the belly in
L. botsfordi
) and ( 3 ) relatively small femoral glands (1.0–3.0 mm, 2–4 % SVL versus 2.4–4.3 mm , 7–14 % SVL in
L. botsfordi
).

From
L. melicus
(Kon Tum Plateau in Ratanakiri, north-eastern Cambodia ,see
Fig. 9
C, D) the new species can be diagnosed by the following: ( 1 ) in having bicolored orange-silvery iris (versus uniformly dark golden iris in
L. melicus
), ( 2 ) by a larger body size in adults ( 30.3–33.9 mm in males; 30.8–34.3 mm in females) (versus 19.5–22.7 mm for males in
L. melicus
), ( 3 ) by a slightly longer tibia in the new species (male TIB:SVL 0.48–0.52 versus 0.46–0.48 in
L. melicus
), and ( 4 ) smaller relative pectoral gland size (PEC/SVL 1–3 % versus 3–6 % in
L. melicus
).
